[1
Date 31 Mar 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC on Wales/Anglesey, 31 Mar 2001 [edited
http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/wales/newsid_1250000/1250863.stm

The u-turn regarding burning comes after pollution tests on a stream
---------------------------------------------------------
First Minister Rhodri Morgan has denied that Anglesey's mass cull of 40 000
sheep is in crisis after the carcass disposal site is switched amid public
health concerns. The u-turn followed pollution concerns and a protest by
residents close to the Mona airfield, where the animals were be stored
ready for burning.
Tests on a stream near the airfield have been conducted by the Environment
after "odors were identified." An agency spokesman said there was "no
doubt" body fluids found in the tributary of the Afon Cefni had seeped from
the airfield. "We are definitely saying the discharge from the Mona site
are definitely body fluids from animal carcasses."
Mr Morgan confirmed the operation would now revert to the assembly's
original plan to bury carcasses at the privately-run Penhesgyn landfill
site, near Menai Bridge. Farmers opposed to the Penhesgyn disposal have
agreed with Agriculture Minister Carwyn Jones to allow up to 10 000
carcasses to be buried at the landfill site.
Mr Jones has been asked to find alternative locations to dispose of the
remaining 30 000 carcasses on the island. An operation is being organized
to transport the carcasses from the airfield and it is reported
slaughtering will be postponed for a day at the abattoir at Gaerwen.
