[2
Date 31 Mar 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org
Source: The Guardian, 31 Mar 2001 [edited
<http://www.guardianunlimited.co.uk/guardianpolitics/story/0,3605,466196,00.html>

The Ministry of Agriculture has been accused of failing to install a
powerful computer system purchased 2 years ago with the intention of
preventing a foot and mouth disease (FMD) epidemic.
MAFF officials purchased a computer tracking system known as EpiMan in the
late 1990s. The system was designed to predict future cases of FMD in the
event of an outbreak of the disease. But government spending cuts meant
funding was switched to BSE and the computer system was instead designated
to track BSE.
The system had been developed by Roger Morris, an authority on FMD based at
Massey University, New Zealand. Speaking to Farmers Weekly, Professor
Morris claimed that the scheme would have been able to speedily predict the
scale of the epidemic. "Undoubtedly fewer cases of the disease would have
occurred. We could have damped the disease down much more quickly."
When the FMD crisis broke in February, MAFF experts decided the system
should be installed, but they could not work out how to do it. MAFF flew in
a team of specialists from New Zealand. Prof Morris said: "The team from
New Zealand took just 4 days to install the system."
However, MAFF denied the accusation, saying Prof Morris contacted MAFF and
offered to install his computer system. MAFF officials said his system was
working alongside their own at the ministry's headquarters.
Prof Morris's computer system holds detailed maps of the UK and information
on factors influencing the spread of the disease, such as weather and
terrain. He said the system could have raised the alarm earlier in the
crisis that MAFF alone could not deal with the outbreak.
The news comes on top of the revelation MAFF failed to undergo any
exercises on the possibility of a FMD epidemic.
